---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// Rewritten against the SnapKey README — the earlier version was written from
// the resume one-liner and got the transport wrong (it's an evdev grab + uinput
// virtual device, not a passive shim).
---

<CaseStudy
	title="SnapDaemon — case study"
	description="A Linux daemon bringing hardware SOCD resolution to any keyboard, via an evdev grab and a virtual uinput device."
	eyebrow="Case study — 2024"
	heading="SnapDaemon"
	lede="Wooting's Snap Tap resolves counter-strafe conflicts in keyboard firmware. SnapDaemon does the same thing in software, on any keyboard Linux can see."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'C++17 · evdev · uinput' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'System daemon' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista/snapdaemon', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista/snapdaemon' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The problem</h2>
		<p>
			Hold <code>A</code> and <code>D</code> at the same time and a normal keyboard reports
			both. The game resolves that however it likes — usually as no movement at all, which is
			exactly the dead zone counter-strafing is trying to avoid. Wooting solved it in firmware
			with Snap Tap: last key pressed wins, and releasing it hands control back to whichever
			opposing key is still held.
		</p>
		<p>
			That fix costs a specific keyboard. SnapDaemon moves the same resolution down into the
			Linux input subsystem, where it works with anything the kernel enumerates.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>How it works</h2>
		<p>
			The daemon takes an exclusive grab on the physical device at
			<code>/dev/input/eventX</code>, then creates a virtual keyboard through
			<code>uinput</code>. Everything the OS reads comes from the virtual device, which puts
			SnapDaemon in the only position where it can rewrite state rather than react to it.
		</p>
		<ol class="cs__steps">
			<li>Grab the real keyboard so no other process sees its raw events.</li>
			<li>Pass every ungrouped key straight through to the virtual device, untouched.</li>
			<li>
				For keys inside a configured group, track press order and emit only the most recent
				one — releasing it immediately re-emits the still-held opposite.
			</li>
		</ol>
		<p>
			Groups live in a plain <code>config.cfg</code> keyed by Linux keycodes, so the pairs
			aren't hardcoded to WASD:
		</p>
		<pre class="cs__pre"><code>{`[Group]
key=30  # KEY_A
key=32  # KEY_D

[Group]
key=17  # KEY_W
key=31  # KEY_S`}</code></pre>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Running it</h2>
		<p>
			It's a daemon, so the controls are signals. That turned out to be the right interface —
			rebinding mid-session shouldn't mean dropping the grab and re-acquiring the device.
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>SIGHUP</strong> — reload <code>config.cfg</code> without restarting.</li>
			<li><strong>SIGUSR1</strong> — toggle the lock, passing all keys through unmodified.</li>
			<li><strong>SIGINT</strong> — ungrab the keyboard, destroy the virtual device, exit clean.</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			A PID file at <code>/var/run/snapkey.pid</code> guards against a second instance, which
			matters more than it sounds: two daemons grabbing and re-emitting the same events will
			happily feed each other forever.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			Input handling is a timing problem before it's a logic problem. Getting the resolution to
			feel instant meant treating every event as state to reconcile, not a message to forward.
		</p>
		<p>
			It also forced a real answer to the failure question. When a process holds an exclusive
			grab on the only keyboard attached, a crash between grab and virtual-device creation
			leaves the machine unusable — so teardown had to be designed before the feature was.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
